19 Public Safety,and Safety. The appointment is subject to the process in accordance with
20 G.S. 143B-9 as if the Adjutant General was a head of a principal State department. The Adjutant
21 General shall serve at the pleasure of the Governor. The Adjutant General, while holding this
22 office, shall be a member of the active North Carolina National Guard. If an appointed Adjutant
23 General does not attain the rank of major general with federal recognition within a reasonable
24 period of time from the date of appointment, the Governor shall replace the Adjutant General
25 with an appointee who meets the criteria in in, and appointed in accordance with, this section. A
26 "reasonable period of time" shall take into account time in grade requirements for promotion or
27 promotions and administrative periods necessary to complete the promotion process.
28 (b) In order to be eligible for appointment as Adjutant General, a person shall be a
29 resident of the State of North Carolina and meet all of the following requirements:
30 (1) The person shall have a total of at least 10 years of commissioned service in
31 any component or components of the Armed Forces of the United States.
32 (2) The person shall have a minimum of three years commissioned service in the
33 Army or Air National Guard within the six-year period previous to the
34 appointment date.
35 (3) The person, at the time of appointment, shall be one of the following:
36 a. A major general with federal recognition or who is eligible for federal
37 recognition.
38 b. A brigadier general with federal recognition or who is eligible for
39 federal recognition and who is eligible for promotion to major general
40 with federal recognition.
41 c. A colonel with federal recognition or who is eligible for federal
42 recognition; who is eligible for promotion and federal recognition as a
43 brigadier general; and who is eligible for promotion to major general
44 with federal recognition.
45 (4) The person shall have completed all service school or other criteria for
46 promotion to general officer with federal recognition.
47 (5) The person shall have a minimum of 12 months in command of either (i) an
48 Army or Air National Guard unit or (ii) a unit in any component of the Armed
49 Forces of the United States.
50 (c) Subject to the approval of the Governor and in consultation with the Secretary of
51 Public Safety, the Adjutant General may appoint:
Senate Bill 710-First Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) A deputy adjutant general, who may hold the same rank as the Adjutant
2 General.
3 (2) Two assistant adjutants general for the Army National Guard and an assistant
4 adjutant general for the Air National Guard, each of whom may hold the rank
5 of brigadier general.
6 The appointees authorized by this subsection shall serve at the pleasure of the Governor. The
7 Adjutant General may also employ staff members and other personnel as authorized by the
8 Secretary and funded."
9 SECTION 5.(b) This Part is effective when it becomes law.
10
11 PART VI. MILITARY JUDGES OF THE NCNG APPOINTMENT MODIFICATIONS
12 SECTION 6.(a) G.S. 127A-50 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 127A-50. Summary courts-martial.
14 (a) In the North Carolina National Guard, not in the service of the United States, summary
15 courts-martial may be appointed by any of the following:
16 (1) Any person who may convene a general or special court-martial.
17 (2) The commander of a battalion, comparable or higher command of the North
18 Carolina Army National Guard, provided that the commander is an officer of
19 the grade of major or above.
20 (3) The commander of a detached squadron, comparable or higher command of
21 the North Carolina Air National Guard, provided that the commander is an
22 officer of the grade of major or above.
23 (b) The court acting under this section shall consist of one officer who shall have the
24 power to administer oaths and try enlisted personnel of each respective command for breaches
25 of discipline and violations of laws governing those organizations. These courts shall also have
26 the power to impose punishments in like manner and to the extent prescribed by the Uniform
27 Code of Military Justice and Manual for Courts-Martial, United States, as shall be in use by the
28 Armed Forces of the United States at the time of the offense, except that noofficer, the state
29 military judge, and a judge advocate detailed to the court as a hearing officer. A summary
30 court-martial shall have the authority to impose fines of not more than five hundred dollars
31 ($500.00), to impose forfeitures of two-thirds pay for one month, to restrict to limits, to impose
32 extra duty, and to reduce the rank of enlisted persons E7 and above by up to two ranks and
33 enlisted persons E6 and below to the rank of E1.
34 (c) No court acting under this section shall have the authority to impose confinement as
35 part of a sentence.
36 (d) There shall be no right during summary courts-martial to demand trial by
37 court-martial."
38 SECTION 6.(b) G.S. 127A-50.1 reads as rewritten:
39 "§ 127A-50.1. Military judges.
40 The Adjutant General shall appoint military judges to preside over courts-martial of the North
41 Carolina National Guard not in federal service. Minimum requirements for appointment as a
42 military judge are:are the following:
43 (1) Certification as a military judge by the Judge Advocate General of the United
44 States Army, Air Force, Navy, Marines, or Coast Guard.
45 (2) Designation as a judge advocate by the Judge Advocate General of the United
46 States Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines, or Coast Guard.
47 (3) Membership in the North Carolina National Guard, the National Guard of
48 another state, or the active or reserve components of the Armed Forces of the
49 United States.
50 (4) A member in good standing for at least 10 years of either of the following:
51 a. The bar of the highest court of this or any other state.
Page 20 Senate Bill 710-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. The bar of a federal court.
2 (5) Hold the rank of lieutenant colonel or above."
3 SECTION 6.(c) Section 6(a) of this Part is effective when it becomes law and applies
4 to summary courts-martial initiated on or after that date. Section 6(b) of this Part is effective
5 when it becomes law and applies to military judges serving on or after that date, except the
6 requirements of G.S. 127A-50.1, as amended by Section 6(b) of this Part, shall only apply to
7 appointments made on or after that date. The remainder of this Part is effective when it becomes
8 law.
9
10 PART VII. EFFECTIVE DATE
11 SECTION 7. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
12 law.
